^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|You could also play "DONT Runouts", but since a penalty double of 1NT is rare I am not sure you need to bother learning them. But just as a point of interest, DONT Runouts work as follows:|
PG| ***** 37 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Over 1N - penalty double, redouble is a single suit (similar to the DONT double of 1NT). The 1N bidder bids 2C, and the re-doubler passes with clubs or corrects to their suit.|
PG| ***** 38 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Suit bids over the double are DONT in nature. They show that suit and a higher ranking suit. So 2C shows clubs and another suit, 2D shows diamonds and a major, 2H shows hearts and spades.|
PG| ***** 39 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Again, just as in regular DONT, the NT bidder passes with 3-card support, and bids the next higher suit with a doubleton. The reason being, the NT bidder has at most 1 doubleton, so you are guaranteed a 4-3 fit at worst.|
PG| ***** 40 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As many of you know, my wife and I play weak 1N openers (10-13). In that case, DONT Runouts work superbly. We even play them over artificial doubles. But if you play strong NT, you are rarely doubled for penalty, so DONT Runouts are probably not a learning priority.|
PG| ***** 41 ***** |


