^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|This was a real interesting hand. 1@C was fine and so was 1@H, although 2@H would also be acceptable. It is borderline between 1@H and 2@H. However, Sandy missed an opportunity. She should bid 3@C (preemptive, 5 clubs) not 2@C. Remember, inverted raises are off in competition. |
PG| ***** 75 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|2@H by Sandy is a limit raise. When you have less than a limit raise, make the LOTT bid. In the minors it is a little tricky because theoretically pard could have only 3 clubs. But in a competitive auction, you should assume at least a 4-card suit. So the LOTT action with Sandy's hand is 3@C.|
PG| ***** 76 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Turns out it doesn't matter, because I am bidding 4@H and Stan has a clear 5@C bid, even over 2@C. On the other hand, Ann  has a clear pass.|
PG| ***** 77 ***** |


AT| 
anniebmisc: I thought with 6 in my hand could go to 5.|
PG| ***** 78 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|At this vulnerability, 5H is dangerous for 2 reasons.|
PG| ***** 79 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One is you can get doubled and go down 2 if I have a weak hand. And the other is, you might push them into a making slam. Yes, although a strict LOTT bid says 5H is ok because we probably have an 11-card fit. It is rarely right to bid 5 over 5 when you are vulnerable, unless you are pretty sure you are making it.|
PG| ***** 80 ***** |


NT|^B@2
anniebmisc: And their non-Vul game is only 400.|
PG| ***** 81 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|After all said and done, 5H doubled works out great (since they make 5C). They actually make 6C should they choose to bid it. In fact, if somebody chats to Stan that Ann has the SK singleton :) he makes 7.|
