up|52|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Stan can count 8 sure tricks-4 spades, 2 diamonds, 2 clubs. He needs one more trick. His best hopes are to establish a heart trick, or take the spade finesse. Playing a heart at trick 2 is fine. However, when Sandy plays the Jack, he should play the King. Sandy could easily have @HQJ or even perhaps @HAJ. |
PG| ***** 108 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Even if Ann wins the HA, Stan has knocked out 2 honors with one of his. And if hearts are 3-2, he is guaranteed a heart trick. Once hearts don't work, he should try for the spade finesse. That doesn't work either, but even on this hand, with all the bad breaks, he should take 8 tricks.|
PG| ***** 109 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|What are the guidelines for bidding over a weak-2?|
PG| ***** 110 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|You need less when you have a fit, more when you do not. |
PG| ***** 111 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If you have 4-card support always bid 4-LOTT. If you have 3-card support, bid 3 most of the time. With 18+ Dummy Points and 3 card support bid game.|
PG| ***** 112 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If you have 15-17 and play Ogust, bid 2N (Ogust) and see if partner has a maximum or not and then decide where to place the contract. Let me expand on this hand and responding to Weak-Twos in general.|
PG| ***** 113 ***** |


AT|

^B@2^*BMM: ^*NSee ^*g:weaktwobids::Constructive Bidding, (LINK  -  Weak Two Bids)^*n  for a great tutorial on Weak-Two bids and responses including Ogust.|
n#|9|at|^^^fIf you do follow the link you can return  HERE  by clicking the  |fp|1|n#|3|at|@L|fp||n^|3|at|   icon button, top left.|
PG| ***** 114 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Stan should consider bidding 4H rather than 2S and 3N on the next round. We have an 8-card fit. In general, when someone pre-empts, it is usually right to play in their suit. On this hand, it turns out that because of the very unlucky lie of the cards, 4H is probably down 1, as the defense will take 3 hearts and 1 diamond. |
PG| ***** 115 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But most of the time, making 4 or even 5 is assured. On many layouts, we will lose only 2 heart tricks, and we often will be able to set up the long spades to pitch a diamond loser. So I think bidding 4H directly over 2H is a good bid. |
PG| ***** 116 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Here is the way to think about this board. When someone opens a Weak-Two and you intend to play in their suit, you know that they have at least 5 HCP, 2 points for the 6-card suit, plus at least 1 point for distribution (no worse than 2 doubletons), giving them a minimum of 8 declarer points. |
PG| ***** 117 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Stan has 18 HCP, 1 length point, 1 quality suit point for 20 points. Therefore N/S have an 8-card fit and at least 26 points, enough to bid game. There is no real reason to bid Ogust, Feature, or any other bid. You only bid Ogust or Feature if you are not sure whether your side has enough for game. On this hand Stan knows his side has enough for game and an 8-card heart fit.|
PG| ***** 118 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|You could make  an argument to bid 2S (assuming that is forcing, I play it is not) because you have such nice spades. However, partner will almost never have 4 spades, so you will usually have at best an 8-card spade fit. And as I said in my comments, the pre-empter's hand has the most value when you play in their suit.|
PG| ***** 119 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Yes, I said you should follow LOTT when responding over a Weak-Two. But I have also said that the LOTT does not prevent you from bidding game with even an 8-card fit if your side has at least 26 points, as North knows is the case here.|
PG| ***** 120 ***** |


